As one of the world’s biggest sports, football has a role to play in raising awareness around key societal challenges such as gender-based violence. On Wednesday when they English Premier League returned to action after 100 days of the Covid-19 lockdown, teams showed solidarity with the Black Lives Matter movement. This follows the death of George Floyd while in police custody in Minneapolis on 25 May which lead to protests in cities throughout the United States. Here in Mzansi, three weeks ago a woman Tshegofatso Pule was stabbed to death and his body was found hanging from a tree.The 28-year-old Tshegofatso Pule was eight months pregnant.In response to the surge in gender-based violence and femicide Orlando Pirates midfielder Linda Mntambo has called on all South Africans to end the culture of silence around gender-based violence and report perpetrators to the police. In a video posted on his Facebook account Mntambo said: "You have the power to stop gender based violence. Let us unite and work togather toward winning the fight against all sorts of violence." WATCH THE VIDEO  Let us Stop?? Gender based Violence! #sawillsurvive A post shared by  Linda (@mntambo_23) on Jun 15, 2020 at 12:32pm PDT